1 Introduction

Marine protected areas (MPAs) are a growing part of the marine conservation toolbox, with 7.4% of the world’s oceans currently protected and, and bodies such as the IUCN calling for 30% protection by 2030. Many of the largest of these MPAs are being implemented in the form of “blue-water” MPAs largely covering pelagic ecosystems, characterized by highly mobile species and fishing fleets using a diverse mix of static and dynamic ocean features. These systems operate very differently from the coastal areas where modern MPA design practices have been developed. Pelagic systems are also characterized by combinations of relatively abundant species targeted by fishing, such as most tuna stocks, and highly threatened species caught as incidental “bycatch” in targeted fishing operations, such as oceanic whitetip sharks. Blue-water MPAs are increasingly being proposed specifically to benefit these by-catch populations while minimizing losses or where possible providing benefits to fisheries.

While the effect of MPAs on fisheries yields is a continuously debated topic, the conservation impacts of MPAs have received less attention of late, due in part perhaps to the perceived obvious nature of the problem: if you prevent fishing of a species within an area, there will be more of that species in that area, and so the conservation benefits of MPAs will increase with MPA size. @hastings2017 clearly illustrates this idea. Using a simple two-species two-patch analytical model, they derive conditions under which MPAs can solve the “weak-stock” problem in which a less productive species is incidentally exploited by a fleet targeting a more valuable and productive stock.

However, as Hastings, Gaines, and Costello (2017) point out, their results depend on a very specific set of assumptions, namely that 1) adults are perfectly sedentary 2) the target and bycatch species overlap perfectly in terms of habitat xx….The authors suggest that the impact of these assumptions should be tested in scenarios under which they are unlikely to apply. We build on @hastings2017 to consider the role of MPAs in reducing bycatch reductino while managing tradeoffs with fisheries under a more realistic model reflecting the dynamics of pelagic ecosystems and fisheries.

The core models underpinning MPA science have largely been based on stylized versions of near-shore reef-style xx what to call that, like coral / rocky / kelp forest, etc xx systems, where multiple species often share common habitat, and adults have reasonable site fidelity while larvae are broadly dispersed. Pelagic ecosystems have vastly different dynamics than coastal seas (Game et al. 2009; Lubchenco et al. 2003), characterized by highly migratory species specialized to take advantage of highly dynamic ocean features such as eddies currents while also utilizing static features such as seamounts. Pelagic ecosystems also support both coastal domestic fishing industries along with highly mobile international high-seas fishing operations. Given these dynamics, it remains unclear how many of the lessons from coastal MPA science are applicable to pelagic ecosystems [@ovando2021XX].

Pelagic ecosystems present both opportunities and challenges for MPAs. The highly productive and mobile nature of targeted fisheries in these systems may mean that highly targeted MPAs can be designed that provide effective conservation at minimal fishery costs. Strategic protection of key aggregation locations may enhance depleted pelagic fisheries [xx that Indian ocean study I can’t remember right now]. xx big question here: how focused do we want this paper to be? is it just about conservation tradeoffs or lack thereof with bycatch species, or is about the net conservation and fishery effects of BWMPAs. I’m inclined the former to tee-up the later xx.

However, the dynamic nature of pelagic systems also creates a risk of unintended conservation consequences of MPAs. When an MPA is implemented on former fishing grounds, fishing fleets have two choices: exit the fishery or move to new fishing grounds. When MPAs redistribute effort away from one area and into another, they can accidentally increase fishing effort on species found within the new fishing grounds (Abbott and Haynie 2012). This problem of policy “leakage” is well known in many environmental fields (citations?) but the general properties of this problem have received relatively little attention in the theoretical or empirical MPA literature [see Abbott and Haynie (2012);(savina2008?);fulton2011a;@baum2003 for notable exceptions]. We fill this gap by

  • Assessing the conditions under which this may be a problem using a generalized simulation environment
    • General insights about design strategy, effect of varying degrees of habitat overlap, etc, tradeoffs with fisheries
  • Given that “it depends” nature of the problem, assess the specific potential for this problem in a case study
    • specific insights about design strategy, effect of varying degrees of habitat overlap, etc, tradeoffs with fisheries

Our goal here is not to provide tactical recommendations on the design of blue-water MPAs, but rather to provide a strategic evaluation of the sensitivity of bycatch populations and targeted fisheries to key unknowns and design choices in MPA planning.

2 Methods

Hastings, Gaines, and Costello (2017) employed a simply model to derive conditions under which MPAs would benefit bycatch species. However they also pointed out that even small increases in model complexity quickly make analytical solutions to the effects of MPAs intractable. As such, we based our numerical analysis on a spatially explicit, multi-species, multi-fleet, bio-economic model we call marlin. Models of MPAs span a wide range of complexity, from simple analytical tools to end-to-end ecosystem models (Fulton et al. 2015). marlin follows a “models of intermediate complexity” (MICE) philosophy (Plagányi et al. 2014) targeted specifically around the role of technical interactions across species. Many MPA models simulate the impacts of MPAs on a single-species level (ovando2021XX?). This can be useful for for example examining the ways in which species-specific life history traits interact with fleet dynamics to influence MPA outcomes. However, bycatch problems are driven by technical interactions, in which fishing effort for a target species incidentally captures another species xx how do we want to talk about this in here? Like usually incidentally, but clearly sometimes people try and catch sharks too xx. marlin accounts for this by allowing the user to simulate an arbitrary number of fleets capable of catching an arbitrary number of species in a spatial area. Different fleets can place different economic value on different species, while also having species-specific selectivity functions. This allows us to simulate bycatch dynamics of MPAs in pelagic ecosystems.

We first ran a series of simulation exeriments designed to explore broad sensitivities of bycatch and fisheries to key factors.

We then ran a focused case study intended to reflect some of the traits of the tuna fisheries of the WCPO, holding constant…

2.2 Simulation Experiments

Given the complexity of the operating model used here, a complete sensitivity analysis across all parameters is not practical. Instead, we focus on the role of XX key attributes of pelagic ecosystems: the degree of spatial overlap between populations, the presence of seasonal migrations, and the potential for ontogenetic shifts in habitat use, and degree of fishing pressure on each species.

2.3 Species & Fleets

Each simulation considers n_distinct(marlin_inputs$scientific_name) species comprised of the top 12 species by landings reported in the tuna fisheries of the Western and Central Pacific Ocean (WCPO). Rough Life history parameters are pulled from FishLife (thorson2020?). For teleost fishes, we assumed that fecundity was proportional to weight-at-age times the maturity ogive. For cartilaginous species, we adopt a fixed fecundity relationship of XX pups per mature individual XX check on what I actually implemented here XX. The unfished spawning stock biomass for each of the included species was tuned in the model to reflect best available estimates from stock assessments.

Each simulation includes a longline and a purse-seine fleet. Each species can have a separate price (USD/kg) and selectivity ogive for each fleet, as dictated by the literature.

Fleets exert a given amount of effort in a patch each time step. The catch resulting from that effort is given by the Baranov (baranov18XX?) equatino

\[C_{f,s,p,t} = \frac{q_{f,s}E_{f,p,t}}{q_{f,s}E_{f,p,t} + m_s} \times \sum_{a=0}^{A}B_{s,p,t,a} \times (1 - e^{-(q_{f,s}E_{f,p,t}S_a + m_s)}) \]

Where \(C\) is catch by fleet \(f\) of species \(s\) in patch \(p\) in timestep t. \(E\) is total effort by that fleet in a patch and time step, \(m\) is natrual mortality for a given species, \(B\) is biomass at age a, and \(S\) is selectivity.

\(q\) is the catchability coefficient for fleet \(f\) and species \(s\).

Fleets distribute themselves in space according to revenue per unit effort

\[R_{f,p,t} = \frac{\sum_{s=1}^{S}v_{f,s}C_{f,s,p,t}}{E_{f,p,t}}\] Where \(v\) is the price per kg of each species. Bycatch in the model is defined through the price. An unregulated species with no commercial value would have \(v = 0\), whereas a regulated and prohibited species might actually have a negative price.

Effort per fleet is set a a constant of 1 per patch, and the model then tunes \(q_{f,s}\) such that given all the other parameters of the model the fishing mortality rate for each species matches the best available level for that species. This is what allows the model to capture bycatch dynamics: A fleet can distribute itself purely based on revenues from target species, but through the \(q\) parameter still exert fishing mortality on other species, even if that species has a price of zero, if those bycatch species inhabit the same patches as the more valuable target species.

2.3.1 Species Overlap

We simulate degrees of species overlap using two parameters, \(\sigma_c\) and \(\sigma_h\). All species start with the assumption that the centroid of their preferred habitat occurs in the center-most patch of teh two dimensional system simulated by marlin. For our simulations, we then generated a random deviation from that default centroid for each species using \(\sigma_c\) in the manner

\[centroid_s \sim normal(center,\sigma_c)\] where s denotes species, and center is the coordinate of the central cell. In this way, the larger \(\sigma_c\) grows, the more variation there is betwen the centroid of the preferred habitat for each species.

We then control the spread of a creatures preferred habitat around that centroid per a Gaussian dispersal kernal in the manner

\[habitat_{p,s} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma_h^2}}e^{-\frac{d_p^2}{2\sigma_h^2}}\]

Where \(d\) is the euclidian distance from the \(centroid_s\) to patch \(p\) and \(\sigma_h\) controls the dispersal of the habitat around that range.

2.3.2 Ontogenetic Shifts

marlin allows for different habitats to be used by adults vs. recruits. For scenarios with ontogenetic shifts ,we assign recruits to a habitat grid that is the inverse of \(habitat_{p,s}\). In this way organisms enter the model living on one area, and then transition to adult habitat at older life stages.

2.3.3 Seasonal Migration

For this paper marlin is set to run with two seasons per year. When seasonal movement is turned on, animals use one habitat matrix in season one, and the inverse of that habitat matrix in season 2.

2.3.4 MPA Design Strategies

MPA design is governed by four general parameters: the number of cells to place inside an MPAs, and the design strategy used to place the MPAs, the species considered in the MPA planning process, and the accuracy of the information used in the planning process.

We consider 5 different MPA placement strategies.

For the “depletion” strategy, MPA locations are prioritized based in proportion to the spawning stock biomass (SSB) of the most depleted species. So, patches with high amounts of highly depleted species are prioritized over patches with high biomass of lightly depleted species.

For the “rate” strategy, MPAs are placed in based on the depletion-weighted catch relative to the total catch in a patch. So, patches where with high rates of catch of depleted species relative to totcal catch are prioritized.

For the “avoid_fishing” strategy, MPAs locations are prioritized inversely to fishery catches. So, patches with low catches are prioritized over patches with high catches.

For the “target_fishing” strategy, MPAs locations are prioritized proportionally to fishery catches. So, patches with high total catches are prioritized over patches with high catches.

For the “area” strategy, we simply assign patches in sequential order until the desired total MPA size is reached.

The information used to inform each MPA design strategy (except area) can include a multiplicative observation error term \(\sigma_{obs}\) where

\[information \sim lnorm(data,\sigma_{obs}) \]

For example, for the depletion scenario, \(\sigma_{obs}\) controls the accuracy of the spatial depletion data used to prioritize MPA placement.

2.4 Case Study

In order to constrain the parameter space somewhat, we also ran a series of case study experiments. Rathere than interating over different habitat configurations and movement dynamics, we fix habitat for each species based on the results of (bradley2021XX?), and set ontogenetic movement and seasonal migrations to FALSE.

2.4.1 MPA Network Optimization

For the case study section, as a point of comparison we calculate an optimized MPA network along with the “rule of thumb” networks based on the design strategies outlined in section XX. The optimization routine is based on an objective function of the form

\[obj = \alpha \times scale(\sum_{s=1}^{S}\frac{ssb_s}{ssb0_s}) + (1 - \alpha) \times scale(\sum_{s=1}^{S}R_s) \]

where \(\alpha\) controls the relative weight assigned to a “conservation” objective based on depletion, relative to an “economic” objective based on revenues. The ‘scale’ function rescales both objective components to the range of 0 to 1 to facilitate interpretation of \(\alpha\) xx come up with a better version of this XX

The optimization routine itself works through a sampling-importance-resampling algorithm. In the first iteration of the algorithm, the marginal contribution of each individual patch to the objective function is calculated. The patch with the highest objective function value is then placed in an MPA. For the remaining iterations, we sample X cells from the remaining non-MPA cells with probability proportional to their marginal value to the objective function in the last iteration. We then calculate the marginal value of each of these cells when individually added to the MPA network begun in the prior step. The cell with the higheset marginal value is then added to the MPA network, and the marginal values of the non-selected but sampled cells are updated based on the values in that iteration. The process then continues until the desired MPA size is reached.

2.5 Assessing Performance

Each model run started at equilibrium conditions and was then run for 40 years (80 seasons. We assessed performance by comparing relevant metrics (e.g. depletion and revenue) under a given scenario with MPAs relative to the values of those same metrics in the simulated counterfactual world identical in every way save for the presencee of MPAs.

The Role of Blue-Water Marine Protected Areas in Bycatch Reduction

What’s the question: How effective are Blue-Water MPAs in reducing fishing mortality of important pelagic bycatch species?

Another angle. There’s going to be a lot of unknowns in designing BWMPA. How much does not fully understanding a few key life history (e.g. movement) matter, and how much does the role that the species plays in the broader fleets portfolio matter

Could simulate habitat from a multivariate normal, where you use the sigma to control how similar rasters are across species

Marine protected areas are increasingly proposed to protect biodiversity in pelagic systems. However, maby paradigms of mpa design come from coastal systems. Here we ask, how likely are blue-water MPAs to provide conservation benefits to bycatch species, and what are the key uncertainties underlying these outcomes? We begin with a general discussion of the ways in which traits of open-ocean systems might influence the conservation performance of BWMPAs. Given the massive parameter space, we then constrain ourselves to a styulized version of the western central pacitic ocean to ask, how feasible is it to provide broad protection of bycatch species through common MPA design paradigms in the context of this system. Our results demonstrate the critical importance of XX and XX in designing MPAs in pelagic systems, and highlight the potential risks of not accounting for XX. Introductionhere

Bycatch is a significant driver of population declines for many pelagic species Sharks, seabirds, mammals, etc MPAs increasingly turned to as a solution for conservation problems, etc. MPA science is largely based on dynamics of coastal systems. Open-ocean ecosystems have very different dynamics that require dedicated research Burgess et al. (2018) estimated the reductions in fishing mortality needed to halt declines for a number of bycatch species Here we ask, what are the key drivers of bycatch conservation outcomes from MPAs? There are all of these species; you reduce fishing mortality. You can either do fisheries management, or you can do MPAs, let’s focus in on the MPA side. This could reduce fishing mortality, or it could do, and it depends on the dynamics of the species and the fleets. When can MPAs reduce fishing mortality enough for bycatch species? And where can you go wrong?

It doesn’t make any sense to ask “do MPAs help bycatch”: the question is obviously it depends. To quickly make this case, we’ll assume that a species is in need of recovery. We then do the simple mako example to show that effects of spatial closure depend on the overlap of habitat and the assumption of fleet dynamics, and provide some empirical evidence that in particular effort redistribution is not unlikely.

Determining the effect of an MPA network on bycatch then will also depend on trying to get close to a tactical model. But, this creates a problem for blue water systems in particular. Can make the argument that given the centrality of relatively static habitat features in coastal MPAs “protect the key habitats” might not be a bad strategy from a conservation strategy. But in highly mobile pelagic systems there (may be) a lot more variables in play. Where should researchers direct their attention?

To reduce the parameter space, we constrain ourselves to a system where 1) we know the species involved 2) we have some sense of the relative depletion and value of the different species and 3) some basic life history of the species. We then vary commonly unknown parameters, particularly preferred habitats, spatial catchability, movement rates etc, and pair these simulations with different MPA designs, and examine the conservation outcomes for bycatch species.

What i don’t like about this

There isn’t an “answer” to this: baring something like “changing the type of density dependence never had any effect greater than XX%,” for anything that on occasion has an impact the answer of “how much” will almost always depend on what else is going on.

So, it seems like there are two real angles of attack here

Pointing out a problem, which to make impactful would require making the case that there is a problem with current design strategies. I.e. "MPAs are often designed like this (simple dispersive models with constant habitat, or MARXSAN style things), and doing that does/does not create problems A tactical evaluation. Picking a handful of high profile MPAs, parameterizing all the knownns as well as possible, iterating over unknowns, and see what the range of outcomes are. Cleaner, more impactful, but also opens it up (depending on the results) to a details fight about very specific modeling choices

Methods

Collect life history for key bycatch species and target species, cite Bradley et al. pulling together species distribution and threats etc. Introduce marlin Parameterize marlin runs with “knowns” from life history of bycatch and target species Highlight key “unknowns” that we will iterate over, e.g. fleet models, density dependent movement, timing of density dependence etc Simulate effects of MPAs given reasonably realistic situations but iterating over key unknowns Evaluate the range of outcomes and key drivers of MPA effects I’m thinking we try and avoid a really specific case study but hard not to accidentally do one without making everything up….

Results Range of likely changes in fishing-induced mortality for the species selected Key drivers of uncertainty in those outcomes, focusing on things that switch states from reduction to increase in mortality How common are conservation tradeoffs between bycatch species? Fishery impacts

Discussion What does this say about BWMPAs and bycatch? Not going to get into design decisions here, depending how common tradeoffs are I think that will be the main focus Highlight any species that frequently induced tradeoffs Tee up future research MPAs in context of other management MPAs as risk reduction strategy Etc.
